  "stage": {
    "id": "foundations",
    "stageNumber": 1,
    "title": "Foundations",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "sequence_to_sequence",
        "title": "Sequence-to-Sequence Models",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Encoder-decoder paradigm\n- Variable-length input/output\n- Foundation for machine translation\n\nIn 2014, Sutskever, Vinyals, and Le at Google introduced a revolutionary idea: use one neural network (the encoder) to read an entire input sequence and compress it into a fixed-size vector, then use another network (the decoder) to generate an output sequence from that vector.\n\nThink of it like a human translator who first reads an entire English sentence, forms a mental understanding of its meaning, and then produces the French translation word by word.\n\nThis encoder-decoder paradigm became the foundation for neural machine translation and later evolved into the Transformer architecture we study in this course.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "attention_mechanism",
        "title": "The Attention Mechanism",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Query-key-value paradigm\n- Weighted aggregation\n- Dynamic focus on relevant information\n\nBahdanau et al. (2015) noticed a critical flaw in early seq2seq models: squeezing an entire sentence into one fixed vector loses information, especially for long sentences.\n\nTheir solution was attention: instead of using just one vector, let the decoder look back at all encoder states and decide which ones are relevant for each output word. It's like having a spotlight that can shine on different parts of the input as needed.\n\nThe mechanism works through queries (what I'm looking for), keys (what's available), and values (what to retrieve). The similarity between query and keys determines attention weights, which are used to compute a weighted sum of values.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "residual_connections",
        "title": "Residual Connections",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Skip connections\n- Gradient flow\n- LayerNorm(x + Sublayer(x))\n\nHe et al. (2016) discovered that very deep networks are hard to train because gradients vanish as they flow backward through many layers. Their elegant solution: skip connections that add the input directly to the output.\n\nImagine a highway with an express lane: information can either take the regular route through the layer's computation, or bypass it entirely via the skip connection. The network learns what to add, not what to transform.\n\nIn the Transformer, every sub-layer (attention and feed-forward) is wrapped with a residual connection: output = x + Sublayer(x). This enables training of the deep 6-layer stacks.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "layer_normalization",
        "title": "Layer Normalization",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Per-example normalization\n- Stabilizes training\n- Independent of batch size\n\nBa, Kiros, and Hinton (2016) proposed layer normalization as an alternative to batch normalization. Instead of normalizing across the batch, it normalizes across features for each individual example.\n\nThink of it as each student grading their own test relative to their own average, rather than comparing to the class average. This makes it independent of batch size and works well for sequence models.\n\nIn the Transformer, layer normalization is applied after each residual connection: LayerNorm(x + Sublayer(x)). This stabilizes training by keeping activations in a reasonable range.",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "byte_pair_encoding",
        "title": "Byte Pair Encoding (BPE)",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Subword units\n- Iterative merging\n- Shared vocabulary\n\nSennrich et al. (2016) introduced BPE to neural MT to solve the rare word problem. Instead of using whole words, BPE builds a vocabulary of subword units by iteratively merging the most frequent character pairs.\n\nImagine learning that 'un' + 'happi' + 'ness' can combine to form 'unhappiness'. Even if you've never seen 'unhappiness' before, you understand its parts. BPE does the same for neural networks.\n\nThe Transformer uses BPE with a shared source-target vocabulary of ~37,000 tokens, allowing it to handle any word by decomposing it into known subwords.",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-1",
      "question": "How does BPE handle rare or unknown words? Answer with a number.",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "It skips them entirely",
        "It breaks them into known subword pieces",
        "It replaces them with a special token"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "It breaks them into known subword pieces",
